nings":["Scottish: habitational name from Dunbar, a place on the North Sea coast near Edinburgh, named with Gaelic <i>dùn</i> ‘fort’ + <i>barr</i> ‘top, summit’.","History: A family of this name were granted the lands of Dunbar by Malcolm III (1058–1093), and later acquired the earldoms of Dunbar and March. These earldoms were then withdrawn from the family by James I in 1434."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dorothy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."],"variants":[{"name":"Dorothee","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."]},{"name":"Dorothie","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Dorothy Agnes Dunbar was born in 1057, in Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland. She married William Sinclair before 1060, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1078, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1057–1078":"1057–1078","1045–1098":"1045–1098","1074–1153":"1074–1153","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1057":"1057","1078":"1078","1045":"1045","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","abt 1075":"umbes 1075","1075":"1075","1074":"1074","before 1060":"enne 1060","Dunbar Castle, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1057–1078":"1057–1078","1045–1098":"1045–1098","1074–1153":"1074–1153","1075–Male":"1075–Kuollut","1057":"1057","1078":"1078","1045":"1045","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","abt 1075":"noin 1075","1075":"1075","1074":"1074","before 1060":"ennen vuotta 1060","Dunbar Castle, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"1057–1078":"1057–1078","1045–1098":"1045–1098","1074–1153":"1074–1153","1075–Male":"1075–Décédé","1057":"1057","1078":"1078","1045":"1045","1153":"1153","1098":"1098","abt 1075":"environ 1075","1075":"1075","1074":"1074","before 1060":"avant 1060","Dunbar Castle, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Écosse","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse","lifeSummary":"Dorothy Agnes Dunbar est née en 1057, à Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Écosse. Elle a épousé William Sinclair avant 1060, à Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils. Elle est décédée en 1078, à l’âge de 21 ans."},"de":{"1057–1078":"1057–1078","1045–1098":"1045–1098","1074–1153":"1074–1153","1075–Male":"1075–Verstorben","1057"